## Pixelz Order System – Architecture & Implementation

### 1\. Background & Business Context

Pixelz helps e-commerce studios meet tight deadlines by providing scalable, AI-powered image retouching. Customers use a portal to create orders, perform checkout and payment, and receive recurring billing.

This submission focuses on a critical flow: completing an order checkout and triggering downstream effects such as email confirmation, invoice generation, and pushing the order to a production system.

**Goal:** Deliver a reliable, observable end-to-end flow that handles failures gracefully.

**Out of Scope:** Recurring billing, real integrations, and full-scale infrastructure.

---

### 2\. Requirements

#### *2.1 Functional*

* **Order Search**

  * Users must be able to **search for existing orders by name**, using partial match queries

* **Checkout flow:**

  * Trigger payment (mocked)

  * On Payment success

    * **Send a confirmation email** to the client. This is a **required business action**.

    * **Generate an invoice** using the mocked Invoice System.

    * **Push the order** to the internal Production System to initiate fulfillment.

  * On Payment error

    * The system must **not trigger any side-effects**.

    * An appropriate failure response must be returned to the client.	

#### *2.2 Non-functional*

* Idempotent checkout logic to avoid double processing

* Retry and fallback on transient failures

* Observability: traceability via OpenTelemetry

* Performance: should not block user flow

---

### 3\. Assumptions & Clarifications

* Email, invoice, and production systems are mocked

* Payment success is the pivot point (safe to proceed afterward)

* Failures in post-payment steps do not roll back payment

* Each side-effect should be retryable and independently trackable  
* The sentence *"we have to create an invoice to our invoice system, otherwise, we need to call our internal Production system"* is interpreted as a **list of tasks to perform after successful checkout**, not conditional logic.  
   That means: after a successful payment, we must:  
- Send a confirmation email to the client.

- Create an invoice in the invoice system.

- Call the Production service to push the order for processing.

These actions are **independent side-effects** triggered after payment, and not conditional on each other.

---

### 4\. Architecture – Phase 1: Monolith MVP

#### *4.1 High-Level Design*

The system is designed as a single-process monolith using Clean Architecture. It contains clear separation of concerns across API, Application, Domain, and Infrastructure layers. All side-effects (email, invoice, production) are handled synchronously in the same process.

*Diagram: Monolith Architecture*

[*![][image1]*](https://viewer.diagrams.net/index.html?tags=%7B%7D&lightbox=1&highlight=0000ff&edit=_blank&layers=1&nav=1&title=Pixelz-Architecture-Order.drawio&dark=auto#Uhttps%3A%2F%2Fdrive.google.com%2Fuc%3Fid%3D1R-1eYmEhB1Ag919ubSm_sK0kXRnBEYHf%26export%3Ddownload#%7B%22pageId%22%3A%22WmfZtAgXlSrt2g1TYUBC%22%7D)*This Architecture focus on the simply and fast delivery for production*

#### *4.2 Sequence Flow*

Client → OrdersController → CheckoutCommand  
          → PaymentGateway  
          → EmailService  
          → InvoiceService  
          → ProductionClient[![][image2]](https://viewer.diagrams.net/index.html?tags=%7B%7D&lightbox=1&highlight=0000ff&edit=_blank&layers=1&nav=1&title=Pixelz-Architecture-Order.drawio&dark=auto#Uhttps%3A%2F%2Fdrive.google.com%2Fuc%3Fid%3D1R-1eYmEhB1Ag919ubSm_sK0kXRnBEYHf%26export%3Ddownload#%7B%22pageId%22%3A%22TSOVq5WKc0q6Y8ll8S79%22%7D)

Steps:

1. Validate order and user

2. Mark as PaymentPending

3. Call mock payment service

4. If successful, update status and call downstream services

#### *4.3 Pros*

* Simple to implement and reason about

* Easy to debug

* No external infra dependencies

#### *4.4 Cons*

* Coupled side-effects can block the flow

* Failure in one service may cause partial state

* Low flexibility and extensibility

#### *4.5 Error Handling*

Each side-effect maintains its own status (Success, Failed, NotStarted). On failure after retries, the order is marked ProcessingFailed. A background job polls and retries failed operations independently.

*Example state fields in OrderSideEffectStatus (1-1 with Orders):* EmailStatus, InvoiceStatus, ProductionStatus

---

### 5\. Architecture – Phase 2: Event-Driven Evolution

#### *5.1 Motivation*

While the MVP is functionally complete, it is limited in resilience and scalability. An event-driven model allows decoupled processing, retry isolation, and better error recovery.

#### *5.2 Design Overview*

* Payment success → write OrderPaid event to outbox

* CDC publishes events

* Handlers for Email, Invoice, and Production consumer independently

*Diagram: Event-Driven Design[![][image3]](https://viewer.diagrams.net/index.html?tags=%7B%7D&lightbox=1&highlight=0000ff&edit=_blank&layers=1&nav=1&title=Pixelz-Architecture-Order.drawio&dark=auto#Uhttps%3A%2F%2Fdrive.google.com%2Fuc%3Fid%3D1R-1eYmEhB1Ag919ubSm_sK0kXRnBEYHf%26export%3Ddownload#%7B%22pageId%22%3A%22eWFAmj6Jg2Gbgj1_nOdi%22%7D)*

#### *5.3 Benefits*

* **Data Consistency**: Events are written within the same local transaction to ensure consistency between business state and event emission. No events are lost.

* **Eventually Consistent Side Effects**: All downstream operations (email, invoice, production, etc.) process events asynchronously and reach consistency over time.

* **Scalable & Idempotent Handlers**: Each side-effect handler is independently scalable and designed to be safely re-executed without unintended consequences.

* **Isolated Retry Logic**: Failures in one handler do not affect others. Each component manages its own retries and error recovery.

* **Extensibility**: New event consumers (e.g. SMS notification, Slack alerts, order cancellation handlers) can be added without modifying the core logic.

#### *5.4 Error Handling*

* User checkout for exist order: check order\_id before process

* Payment fail: Return fail checkout

* Payment success but app crash, not update order status: cronjob running will relay order haven't been processed (status created). The order will be re-pay, but don't worry, we use order\_id for idempotent payment, it cannot charge again. 

*  Payment success but side-effect service not working such as EmailService cannot send mail for some reason,...: The event paid is persistent, and has status for each side-effect operator in ***OrderSideEffectStatus***,  it will be processed when the side-effect service is running. It means sending mail can re-process after that and ensure user receipt email at least one.

#### *5.5 Comparison: Monolith vs Event-Driven*

| Aspect | Monolith MVP | Event-Driven |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Delivery Speed | Fast | Moderate |
| Simplicity | High | Medium |
| Resilience | Low | High |
| Retry Logic | Inline | Per handler |
| Scalability | Low | High |
| Observability | Central logs | Distributed tracing |
| Extendability | Medium | High |

### 6\. Data Models

* **Users**: End users such as customers, art directors,..

* **Orders**: The main domain entity that drives all downstream processes.

* **Payments, Invoices, EmailLogs**: Created during checkout as side-effect results.In Monolith mode, they may be stored centrally; in Event-Driven mode, they are owned by their respective services.

* **OrderSideEffectStatus**: Tracks the execution state of downstream operations (e.g., email sent, invoice created, pushed to production).

[![][image4]](https://viewer.diagrams.net/?tags=%7B%7D&lightbox=1&highlight=0000ff&edit=_blank&layers=1&nav=1&title=Pixelz-Architecture-Order.drawio&dark=auto#Uhttps%3A%2F%2Fdrive.google.com%2Fuc%3Fid%3D1R-1eYmEhB1Ag919ubSm_sK0kXRnBEYHf%26export%3Ddownload#%7B%22pageId%22%3A%22UfbOruiken60PSyAf4HN%22%7D)

- Orders \- Invoices: 1-1,   
- Orders \- Payments: 1-1  
- Orders \- EmailLogs: 1-n, it can be send duplicate or more email to notification  
- Orders \- Users: 1-n, users can create many orders

### 7\. API Design

| Endpoint | Method | Description |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| /orders/query={name} | GET | Search orders by name |
| /orders/{id}/checkout | POST | Trigger checkout flow |
| /orders/{id} | GET | Get Order status |
| /webhook/payment | POST | Optional for Payment progress |
| /webhook/production | POST | Optional for Production progress |

---

### 8\. Application Flow

The CheckoutCommandHandler validates the order, processes payment via a mock gateway, then triggers all side-effects (email, invoice, production) using a retry helper.

Side-effects update their status in the order. If any fail after retries, the order is left in a recoverable ProcessingFailed state.

### 9\. Data Integrity

This system enforces data integrity across payment and asynchronous side-effects through several design choices:

* **Transactional Boundary:** The order and payment are handled as a single atomic unit. Side-effects (email, invoice, production push) are only triggered after a successful payment and do not affect the payment outcome.

* **Status Tracking:** Each side-effect updates its own status field (**EmailStatus, InvoiceStatus, ProductionStatus**) in the **OrderSideEffectStatus** table. This enables recovery, avoids duplication, and maintains observability.

* **Retry-safe Handlers:** All side-effect processors are designed to be idempotent and can be safely retried without corrupting the system state.

* **Persistent Events:** Event **OrderPaid** are written to durable storage before being processed. If a handler fails or crashes, the event will be re-processed later.

* **Recovery Mechanisms:** Orders stuck if service crashes are marked as **Created**. A background job continuously scans for and retries these orders.

---

### 10\. Observability & OpenTelemetry

* Uses System.Diagnostics.Activity for distributed tracing

* Traces: Checkout → Payment → Email → Invoice → Production

* Tags: order.id, retry count, step name

* Supports exporting to OTLP/Jaeger/Zipkin

It will easy to manage performance & trace in grafana, flow is:

### 11\. Codebase Structure

src/  
├── API/                \# Web layer, controllers  
├── Application/        \# Use cases, DTOs, retry logic  
├── Domain/             \# Core entities, enums, interfaces  
├── Infrastructure/     \# Mocks for email, payment, production  
├── Persistence/        \# InMemory DB or EF Core (optional)  
├── Test/     		\# Unit test

---

### 12\. Scaling the Codebase for 10–20 Engineers

* Modular by domain: Orders, Payments, Invoice, etc.

  src/

  ├── OrderService		    \# Management Order				   
  	├── API/                \# Web layer, controllers  
  	├── Application/        \# Use cases, DTOs, retry logic  
  	├── Domain/             \# Core entities, enums, interfaces  
  ├── PaymentService/        \# Separate payment domain  
  ├── InvoiceService/        \# Separate invoice domain  
  ├── ProductionService/     \# Separate production domain (optional)


* Interfaces isolate business logic from infrastructure with Clean Architect

* CI/CD per module

---

### 13\. Scalability & Performance Considerations

#### *Monolith MVP:*

* Blocking HTTP flow limits throughput

* Long-running side-effects delay checkout response

* Mitigations: async Task.WhenAll() for side-effect operator or change it to background jobs

#### *Event-Driven:*

* Side-effect handlers can scale independently

* Async queue good for traffic spikes

* Retry/dead-letter logic improves resilience

#### *Database:*

* Sharding the Orders table by creation time (e.g., monthly) to reduce write contention.

* Separate Read, Write database, replicate Order to Elastic Search to improve performance and fulltext search
